&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Romesh Thappar v. State of Madras&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;There is no need to resort to Article 226 in the first instance before approaching the Supreme Court under Article 32. This position was clarified in the case of &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Romesh Thappar v. State of Madras&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Romesh Thappar filed a petition challenging a decision by the State of Madras banning the entry and circulation of his leftist journal- &amp;quot;Cross Roads&amp;quot; arguing that the State&amp;rsquo;s justification for the ban on the basis of &amp;ldquo;public safety&amp;rdquo; was too broad.&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Advocate General who appeared on behalf of the State of Madras also raised an additional issue whereby he argued that the petitioner has to first approach the High Court under Article 226 and only when he had exhausted that remedy, he could bring his grievances to the Supreme Court.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Supreme Court of India agreed with a petition asserting that powers granted under the Madras Maintenance of Public Order Act, 1949 enabled the State to unconstitutionally restrict free expression.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The High Court has the jurisdiction under &lt;strong&gt;Article 226&lt;/strong&gt; to issue directions, orders or writs for the enforcement of Fundamental Rights.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A High Court is empowered to issue directions, orders, or writs for the enforcement of a Fundamental Right and for any other purpose those include:
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Habeas corpus&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Mandamus&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Prohibition&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Quo warranto&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;Certiorari&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article 32&lt;/strong&gt; of the Indian Constitution has been described as the &amp;lsquo;heart and soul&amp;rsquo; of the Indian Constitution by Dr B. R. Ambedkar.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It gives a citizen the right to approach the Supreme Court to get resorted to any of the fundamental rights in case of their violation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is also known as the Right to Constitutional Remedies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;315&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) is a &lt;strong&gt;Central recruiting agency&lt;/strong&gt; responsible for the appointment and examination of All India Services and Group A and B of Central Services.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The UPSC was&lt;strong&gt; formed&lt;/strong&gt; on &lt;strong&gt;1st October 1926&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;headquarters&lt;/strong&gt; of UPSC is in &lt;strong&gt;New Delhi&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;current chairman of UPSC&lt;/strong&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;Manoj Soni&lt;/strong&gt;. ( May 2022)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;first chairman &lt;/strong&gt;of UPSC was&lt;strong&gt; Sir Ross Baker&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&lt;strong&gt; chairman and other members&lt;/strong&gt; of UPSC are appointed by the &lt;strong&gt;President of India&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

